<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-10-17T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-10-17T20:00:00-05:00" n="91" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d91">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94 Conference/41: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-18T10:00:00+09:00">October 18, 1937—10
                                        a.m.</date><lb/>[Received October 17—11:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>479. Embassy’s 476 [<hi rend="italic">475</hi>], October 15, 5 p.m.,
                                paragraph 2, Nine Power Treaty Conference. It may be well to record
                                that one of the arguments which I used in my conversation with
                                Hirota was that the proposed Conference would offer Japan a forum to
                                present the views for which purpose it is sending so-called good
                                will envoys to America and Europe.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>